english:
  title: Record of Goam
  author: Lee Saek
  language: eng
  text: |-
    In the year Xin-hai, Cheon Gyeong of Jogyesan—the great meditation master—is the younger brother of Choi, the Minister of War, with whom I passed the examination in the same year. I had heard long of the minister's younger brother, yet knew not that he had become a Buddhist monk. When we met at Gwangam, I saw his face mirrored his brother's, and my sorrow deepened. The minister has no son, and now his brother too has taken this path—what fate is this?

    One day he came to me and said, "My name is Goam, bestowed by Master Kugok. I love the ancient, and I dwell in stone. Because I cherish the old, I stand apart from this present world; because I make my home in the rock, I remain distant from the flatlands. In my early studies, I sought this to commune with the ancients and to escape the vulgar world—not to elevate the Buddha as ultimate truth. I humbly request a word from you to mark this path."

    I replied, "The younger brother of my fellow graduate is my younger brother too—how could I withhold my words? You have turned from your brother's way and entered another path. Yet you honor his friend and seek learning to admire our Way. How could I withhold my words? And yet, your learning is not our learning, and our learning is not yours. Does this not risk becoming mere gossip repeated along the road?"

    Pan Gu lies far in the distant past. Great Yu established the high mountains and great rivers. Men found level ground and dwelt upon it. Yet those craggy peaks and deep gorges, where human footsteps seldom tread, became the lairs of tigers, wolves, apes, and birds. And yet mountains and marshes exchange their vital breath, sending forth clouds and rain to irrigate the fields and valleys. Since the Yellow Emperor's well-field system, the benefits have flowed abundantly to this day. Those who eat their fill and live in ease, yet know not how these blessings came to be, are foolish indeed. I have spoken thus often to the young, though I know not if they heed me. Only this meditation master seems to grasp it—for his name reflects his true nature.

    When the master seeks the meaning behind his own naming, he aspires to spread compassion through the three paths of suffering, and to walk the Way through the three temporal realms, holding in his heart a unity without past or future, a equality that knows no high or low. He would make awakened nature overflow in all directions, pure and luminous everywhere. Then the ancient and the present, the craggy stone and the level plain, all become the complete and wondrous workings within a single span of the heart. Facing the wall in meditation, the ten directions of empty space dissolve entirely. How then could there remain any distinction between the vertical and the horizontal?

    Yet though the master has cast aside his form, he has not hidden his name—he is not one indifferent to the world's teaching. Therefore I invoke the Yellow Emperor and Great Yu, to illuminate one facet of this truth, and conclude with his own teaching. Let the master choose his own way.

    Whose strength allows the master to dwell where he dwells? Whose strength provides what the master eats? Brother of my fellow graduate—I cannot refrain from speaking plainly to you from the heart.
  footnotes:
    - Goam (古巖) literally means 'ancient rock'—a Buddhist monastic name chosen to reflect both his love of antiquity and his mountain hermitage.
    - The 'three paths of suffering' (三塗) and 'three temporal realms' (三際) are Buddhist concepts referring to realms of suffering and the past, present, and future.
    - The reference to Pan Gu, Yu the Great, and the Yellow Emperor's well-field system grounds Buddhist practice within the Confucian historical tradition, suggesting a reconciliation between the two ways.
    - Lee Saek's closing rhetorical questions about who provides the monk's dwelling and sustenance subtly remind him of his worldly dependence, a gentle critique of Buddhist renunciation.
    - The wall-facing (面壁) alludes to Bodhidharma's meditation practice, suggesting the dissolution of all dualistic distinctions in enlightenment.
